The Soviet Union signed several peace treaties throughout its existence. One notable example is the Treaty of Riga, which was signed on March 18, 1921, between the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic and Poland. This treaty established the border between Russia and Poland, with the new Polish-Soviet border being approximately 3,500 kilometers in length.

Another significant peace treaty signed by the Soviet Union is the Treaty of Moscow, also known as the Soviet-Polish Alliance Treaty, which was signed on April 28, 1920. This treaty marked an alliance between the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic and Poland against the German Reich during World War I.

The Soviet Union also participated in the Treaty of Rapallo with Germany on April 16, 1922, which aimed to improve relations between the two nations after World War I. Additionally, there was the Soviet-Turkish Friendship and Trade Agreement signed on October 17, 1921, which established diplomatic and trade ties between the Soviet Union and Turkey.

Furthermore, the Soviet Union signed a peace treaty with Finland on October 14, 1947, known as the Treaty of Paris, and another one with Romania on February 10, 1948.

Methadone is primarily metabolized by three enzymes in the human body: CYP2B6, CYP3A4, and UGT2B7. These enzymes are found in various tissues throughout the body, including the liver and small intestine.

CYP2B6 is involved in the N-demethylation of methadone to form E- and alpha-hydroxymethyl-methadone. 

The CYP3A4 enzyme, on the other hand, plays a key role in the hydroxylation of methadone at the 7-alpha position, resulting in the formation of 2-ethylidene-1,5-dimethyl-3,3-diphenylpyrrolidine.

UGT2B7 is responsible for glucuronidation, which is a process by which a sugar molecule (glucuronic acid) is attached to methadone, making it more water-soluble and easier to excrete from the body.

These enzymes work together in the liver to metabolize approximately 30-50% of the administered dose. The remaining amount is excreted unchanged or as conjugated metabolites through the kidneys into the urine.

It's worth noting that this metabolic pathway can vary slightly depending on genetic variations, age, and health status of an individual.
